High electrical conductivity and wide band gaps—leading to high optical transparencies—are sought but seemingly mutually exclusive properties. In this context, the transparent conductive oxides (TCOs) are a special class of materials that combine both these properties. Depending on the donor (electrons) or acceptor (holes) level in the band gap of such materials, they are either n- or p-type, with carrier concentration (n, p) and optical band gap (Eg\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
