				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${E}_{g}$$\end{document}) typically around 1016–1021 cm−3 and 3 eV, respectively. The most employed TCOs at industrial scale—Sn-doped In2O3 (ITO), Al-doped ZnO (AZO) and F-doped SnO2 (FTO)—have n-type conductivity; among them, ITO stands out with electrical conductivity around 103 S cm−1 and transparency above 80% in the visible range [1, 2]. N-type TCOs have been reported and explored for more than half a century, and they dominate the transparent electronics market upon their two main applications: firstly, as transparent electrodes for flat panel displays and photovoltaic cells and secondly, as active layer for transparent thin film transistors (TFT), UV light-emitting diodes (LED), gas sensors or other transparent electronic devices [3, 4]. However, challenges are still faced to find a matching p-type counterpart. (Extensive reviews can be found in [5–10].) The unveiling of a p-type material with similar properties would open a new era in transparent electronics, by promoting the fabrication of fully transparent active devices such as p–n junctions [6, 11], or complementary transistors [12–14]. This would open a new range of invisible electronics devices including smart windows [3, 15, 16], transparent UV LEDs [17, 18], solar-cell heterojunctions [19, 20], gas sensors [21–24], electromagnetic shielding [25], etc. Since the first report of a semitransparent p-type oxide, NiO [26], a large variety of materials has been investigated as a p-type TCOs suitable for applications:
Binary oxides: ZnO [9, 27–29], B6O[9] [30], In2O3 [31], NiO [24, 26, 32, 33], SnO/SnOx [34–37] and β-Ga2O3 [38–40].
Mixed oxides: In2O3–Ag2O [41, 42];
Chromium based oxides: LaCrO3 [43], Cr2O3 [44, 45];
Ag-, Cu-, Pd- and Pt-based delafossites [46–56];
Layered oxychalcogenides: LaCuOS [57–59] and LaCuOSe [60];
Spinel oxides: NiCo2O4 [61, 62], ZnCo2O4 [63, 64], ZnIr2O4 [63] and ZnRh2O4 [65, 66], etc.;
Others: SnSeO [67], Ba2BiTaO6 [68], SrCu2O2 [69–71], [Cu2S2][Sr3Sc2O5] [72] or La2/3Sr1/3VO3 [73].

From a general point of view, these materials have failed to fully comply with the requirements of a p-type TCO for application purposes as they demonstrate either low conductivity or low transparency. The electrical conductivity (σ) of a material is directly proportional to the carrier concentration (ne,h) and carrier mobility (μe,h) with the last term depending on the carrier scattering relaxation time (τ) and the effective mass (me,h*) of the carriers [74]:1σ=ne,hμe,he=ne,he2τme,h∗\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
